===Verb===
{{en-verb|binds|binding|bound|bound|past_ptc2=bounden|past_ptc2_qual=rare}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To tie; to confine by any [[ligature]].
#* {{rfdate}} {{w|Shakespeare}}
#*: They that reap must sheaf and '''bind'''.
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To cohere or stick together in a mass.
#: ''Just to make the cheese more '''binding'''
#* {{rfdate}} {{w|Mortimer}}
#*: clay '''binds''' by heat.
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To be restrained from motion, or from customary or natural action, as by friction.
#: ''I wish I knew why the sewing machine '''binds''' up after I use it for a while.''
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To exert a binding or restraining influence.
#: ''These are the ties that '''bind'''.''
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[tie]] or [[fasten]] tightly together, with a cord, band, ligature, chain, etc.
#: ''to '''bind''' grain in bundles; to '''bind''' a prisoner.''
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To confine, restrain, or hold by physical force or influence of any kind.
#: ''Gravity '''binds''' the planets to the sun.''
#: ''Frost '''binds''' the earth.''
#* {{rfdate}} Job xxviii. 11.
#*: He '''bindeth''' the floods from overflowing.
#* {{rfdate}} Luke xiii. 16.
#*: Whom Satan hath '''bound''', lo, these eighteen years.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[couple]].
# {{lb|en|figuratively}} To oblige, restrain, or hold, by authority, law, duty, promise, vow, affection, or other social tie.
#: ''to '''bind''' the conscience; to '''bind''' by kindness; '''bound''' by affection; commerce '''binds''' nations to each other.''
#* {{rfdate}} {{w|Milton}}
#*: Who made our laws to '''bind''' us, not himself.
# {{lb|en|legal}} To put (a person) under definite legal obligations, especially, under the obligation of a bond or covenant.
# {{lb|en|legal}} To place under legal obligation to serve.
#: ''to '''bind''' an apprentice; '''bound''' out to service''
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To protect or strengthen by applying a band or binding, as the edge of a carpet or garment.
# {{lb|en|transitive|archaic}} To make fast (a thing) about or upon something, as by tying; to encircle with something.
#: ''to '''bind''' a belt about one''
#: ''to '''bind''' a compress upon a wound.''
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To cover, as with a bandage.
#: ''to '''bind''' up a wound.''
# {{lb|en|transitive|archaic}} To prevent or restrain from customary or natural action.
#: ''certain drugs '''bind''' the bowels.''
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To put together in a cover, as of books.
#: ''The three novels were '''bound''' together.''
# {{lb|en|transitive|chemistry}} To make two or more elements stick together.
# {{lb|en|transitive|computing}} To associate an [[identifier]] with a value; to associate a variable name, method name, etc. with the content of a storage location.
#* '''2008''', Bryan O'Sullivan, John Goerzen, Donald Bruce Stewart, ''Real World Haskell'' (page 33)
#*: We '''bind''' the variable <code>n</code> to the value <code>2</code>, and <code>xs</code> to <code>"abcd"</code>.
#* '''2009''', Robert Pickering, ''Beginning F#'' (page 123)
#*: You can '''bind''' an identifier to an object of a derived type, as you did earlier when you bound a string to an identifier of type <code>obj</code>{{...}}
# {{lb|en|UK|dialect}} To [[complain]]; to [[whine]] about something.
#* '''1980''', Iris Murdoch, ''Nuns And Soldiers''
#*: "But it's not much good piling up the pix if I can't sell them."<br>"Oh do stop '''binding'''. Think of something. How will we eat, where will we sleep?"

